People learn in blocked but not in interleaved curricula
Human performance in mixed curricula lends evidence to SEM prediction
better than interleaved followed by blocked
- In prediction learning task with two schemas, blocked learning was better than interleaved learning.
- Evidence against standard connectionist model which predicts catastrophic interference in blocked curriculum.
- Better learning in blocked curriculum supports models that segment representations based on prediction error.
- These models posit that poor learning in interleaved curricula is due to excessive event segmentation / latent cause inference.
Event segmentation theory (SEM): blocked curriculum supports correct latent cause inference
- Blocked curricula give rise to few but pronounced prediction errors that signal event boundaries
- Interleaved curricula give rise to noisy prediction error signal that causes excessive segmentation
